00:03:49.960 --> 00:03:51.760
that I've done as
well, and perhaps I

00:03:51.760 --> 00:03:55.340
can accelerate your learning
curve a bit in that process.

00:03:55.340 --> 00:03:59.150
And speak a little bit about
my own story of how I evolved

00:03:59.150 --> 00:04:03.110
and the things that have
changed over time for me

00:04:03.110 --> 00:04:04.360
as an investor.

00:04:04.360 --> 00:04:07.860
So the way it begins--
my technical training

00:04:07.860 --> 00:04:09.260
is that of an accountant.

00:04:09.260 --> 00:04:11.650
I'm a CPA, professionally.

00:04:11.650 --> 00:04:16.339
My father was an accountant and
that was what my degree was in.

00:04:16.339 --> 00:04:19.860
And I always tell people
when they're sort of trying

00:04:19.860 --> 00:04:22.720
to figure out what it
is they want to do,

00:04:22.720 --> 00:04:26.310
among the things that would be
a reasonable choice for what

00:04:26.310 --> 00:04:28.510
you're studying,
would be accounting.

00:04:28.510 --> 00:04:30.310
And people ask me,
"why accounting?"

00:04:30.310 --> 00:04:32.830
And I said, well, if you're
going to go to Germany,

00:04:32.830 --> 00:04:37.420
and you wanted to be a
successful person in Germany,

00:04:37.420 --> 00:04:41.700
what would be the very first
thing that you should do?

00:04:41.700 --> 00:04:44.180
And my answer is, you
should learn German,

00:04:44.180 --> 00:04:46.640
because that is the
language that people

00:04:46.640 --> 00:04:49.450
are going to communicate
in, and work in, in Germany.

00:04:49.450 --> 00:04:51.730
So if you want to go
to Germany, and you

00:04:51.730 --> 00:04:54.240
want to be a
success of any sort,

00:04:54.240 --> 00:04:57.010
I think it would be very hard
to do that without having

00:04:57.010 --> 00:04:58.440
a working knowledge of German.

00:04:58.440 --> 00:05:01.570
Well similarly, in
business-- and by business,

00:05:01.570 --> 00:05:05.760
let's translate that further
to investing-- the language

00:05:05.760 --> 00:05:07.320
of business is accounting.

00:05:07.320 --> 00:05:11.930
So to understand what's going
on-- you don't need to be CPA,

00:05:11.930 --> 00:05:14.784
but I think it's very important
to have a rudimentary knowledge

00:05:14.784 --> 00:05:16.450
of what accounting
is, and how it works,

00:05:16.450 --> 00:05:20.150
and what words and
numbers mean when they're

00:05:20.150 --> 00:05:22.980
in the context of financial
statements in business

00:05:22.980 --> 00:05:24.510
and the language of accounting.

00:05:24.510 --> 00:05:26.090
So that's how I started.

00:05:26.090 --> 00:05:30.450
And similar to, I
think, many people

00:05:30.450 --> 00:05:33.470
as they begin to go
down the path of trying

00:05:33.470 --> 00:05:38.830
to become an investor, I had a
very strong quantitative bias

00:05:38.830 --> 00:05:40.840
in selecting investments.

00:05:40.840 --> 00:05:45.262
And one of the ways I would
describe that, and one

00:05:45.262 --> 00:05:46.720
of the tendencies
that we all have,

00:05:46.720 --> 00:05:49.780
especially when we're starting
out, for a variety of reasons,

00:05:49.780 --> 00:05:54.480
is to have quantitative metrics
that you really can rely on.

00:05:54.480 --> 00:05:56.879
And one of the reasons
that that would be case,

00:05:56.879 --> 00:05:58.670
is when you're starting
out and you haven't

00:05:58.670 --> 00:06:00.520
done this a whole
lot, you'd really

00:06:00.520 --> 00:06:04.470
like to have some confidence
supplied by something external

00:06:04.470 --> 00:06:06.070
that you're on the right path.

00:06:06.070 --> 00:06:10.860
And if you can do some
well-established, well-trod

00:06:10.860 --> 00:06:14.390
paths of disciplines of
things that have worked-- boy,

00:06:14.390 --> 00:06:17.890
that seems like a pretty
good basis to make a decision

00:06:17.890 --> 00:06:20.250
and to think about what's
going to happen in the future.

00:06:20.250 --> 00:06:24.520
And there is absolutely nothing
in the world wrong with that.

00:06:24.520 --> 00:06:25.280
I encourage that.

00:06:25.280 --> 00:06:27.290
That's really the
best way to start,

00:06:27.290 --> 00:06:29.760
but I think that is
only a partial step

00:06:29.760 --> 00:06:34.664
along the journey of becoming
an accomplished investor.

00:06:34.664 --> 00:06:37.610
That worked spectacularly
well for Ben Graham

00:06:37.610 --> 00:06:41.870
in the 1930s, who's the
grandfather of all investing

00:06:41.870 --> 00:06:44.980
and the professor who
really taught Warren Buffett

00:06:44.980 --> 00:06:46.244
the disciplines of investing.

00:06:46.244 --> 00:06:48.660
But that was a period of time
when we were just coming out

00:06:48.660 --> 00:06:50.130
of the Depression,
and there were

00:06:50.130 --> 00:06:53.240
a lot of securities
that were mathematically

00:06:53.240 --> 00:06:55.290
and quantitatively cheap.

00:06:55.290 --> 00:06:58.660
So it was a great technique,
a great discipline.

00:06:58.660 --> 00:07:02.380
It had not been
practiced, but that pond

00:07:02.380 --> 00:07:05.540
has gotten a little over-fished.

00:07:05.540 --> 00:07:08.470
So today, while it's important
to know the technical skills,

00:07:08.470 --> 00:07:10.140
to know the accounting,
to know things

00:07:10.140 --> 00:07:13.590
like the net working capital,
and to think about price

00:07:13.590 --> 00:07:15.870
earnings ratios a price
to book value ratios,

00:07:15.870 --> 00:07:18.580
and have the series of
quantitative metrics

00:07:18.580 --> 00:07:20.570
that would tell you
something is cheap,

00:07:20.570 --> 00:07:21.830
that's good as far as it goes.

00:07:21.830 --> 00:07:23.400
But it doesn't tell you enough.

00:07:23.400 --> 00:07:24.760
There are more things.

00:07:24.760 --> 00:07:27.595
And I call the notion of
doing that sort of work, which

00:07:27.595 --> 00:07:28.970
is the first step,
and you really

00:07:28.970 --> 00:07:33.010
should do it-- that's the
idea of spotting value.

00:07:33.010 --> 00:07:37.160
So it's a picture of
time stands still.

00:07:37.160 --> 00:07:40.110
When you're looking at a picture
of something that you think

00:07:40.110 --> 00:07:42.640
is worth this, and
it's selling for this.

00:07:42.640 --> 00:07:44.212
So there's a price a gap there.

00:07:44.212 --> 00:07:45.836
And you want to buy
it at this, and you

00:07:45.836 --> 00:07:47.150
think it will get to that.

00:07:47.150 --> 00:07:50.270
And that that's great if it
works, but that's a picture.

00:07:50.270 --> 00:07:52.620
What I have evolved
to, and the path

00:07:52.620 --> 00:07:55.680
that I've been on for a long
time-- and the reason I got

00:07:55.680 --> 00:07:58.481
on that path is because I found
that that notion of spotting

00:07:58.481 --> 00:08:00.230
value and thinking
that there's value gaps

00:08:00.230 --> 00:08:02.710
would close right after I
showed up to buy some stock,

00:08:02.710 --> 00:08:04.240
it didn't work.

00:08:04.240 --> 00:08:08.160
So it's not as if I found that
technique, and I learned that,

00:08:08.160 --> 00:08:10.050
and it worked, and
produced great wealth.

00:08:10.050 --> 00:08:11.140
It didn't.

00:08:11.140 --> 00:08:12.862
So you gotta take
the next step and try

00:08:12.862 --> 00:08:14.070
to figure something else out.

00:08:14.070 --> 00:08:17.170
So I moved from spotting
value to spotting

00:08:17.170 --> 00:08:20.760
the creation of value,
value creators as opposed

00:08:20.760 --> 00:08:21.960
to value spotters.

00:08:21.960 --> 00:08:24.550
So instead of a snapshot,
instead of a picture,

00:08:24.550 --> 00:08:25.410
how about a movie?

00:08:25.410 --> 00:08:26.951
What's this movie
going to look like?

00:08:26.951 --> 00:08:30.150
How's this reel going
to unfurl over time?

00:08:30.150 --> 00:08:32.770
So instead of saying that I
firmly believe that something

00:08:32.770 --> 00:08:35.799
is worth this, I'm now
asking myself, well,

00:08:35.799 --> 00:08:37.850
what will it be worth next year?

00:08:37.850 --> 00:08:38.900
And the year after that?

00:08:38.900 --> 00:08:39.900
And the year after that?

00:08:39.900 --> 00:08:41.572
And the decade after that?

00:08:41.572 --> 00:08:43.030
And to have some
sense of something

00:08:43.030 --> 00:08:47.014
that is increasing in value over
time at an appropriate rate.

00:08:47.014 --> 00:08:48.680
Well, that's what I'm
really hunting for

00:08:48.680 --> 00:08:52.460
and that's what I'm really
trying to find and spot.

00:08:52.460 --> 00:08:56.090
And I think this
has applications,

00:08:56.090 --> 00:08:58.290
not just for investing,
but for leadership,

00:08:58.290 --> 00:08:59.665
for management,
for relationships

00:08:59.665 --> 00:09:01.470
that you would have
on a social, as well

00:09:01.470 --> 00:09:06.720
as a professional basis. so it's
an integrated thought as to how

00:09:06.720 --> 00:09:09.150
my life is unfurling.

00:09:09.150 --> 00:09:12.940
So with that thought
in mind, I came up

00:09:12.940 --> 00:09:17.360
with a 4-Point view of what
it is that I'm specifically

00:09:17.360 --> 00:09:20.350
looking for, and how I
specifically think about things

00:09:20.350 --> 00:09:21.850
that I might invest in.

00:09:21.850 --> 00:09:24.670
So the first thing that
I look to invest in,

00:09:24.670 --> 00:09:27.140
is a profitable business
with good returns

00:09:27.140 --> 00:09:30.230
on capital, that doesn't use
too much leverage to do it.

00:09:30.230 --> 00:09:32.880
And again, each and
every one of those words

00:09:32.880 --> 00:09:36.050
came about because I
made a mistake somewhere

00:09:36.050 --> 00:09:36.960
along the line.

00:09:36.960 --> 00:09:39.610
Things did not work
and as a consequence,

00:09:39.610 --> 00:09:41.160
it was a hard,
searing lesson where

00:09:41.160 --> 00:09:42.560
I lost some of my own money.

00:09:42.560 --> 00:09:44.810
And as [INAUDIBLE] said in
his introduction, I'm cheap

00:09:44.810 --> 00:09:46.480
and I really hate losing money.

00:09:46.480 --> 00:09:50.540
So hard lessons are
learned of the kind that

00:09:50.540 --> 00:09:52.690
sink in and sear most deeply.

00:09:52.690 --> 00:09:56.020
So the profitable business
with good returns on capital.

00:09:56.020 --> 00:09:58.950
Now, you live in a
part of the world

00:09:58.950 --> 00:10:03.400
here where there are a lot
of dreams, a lot of venture

00:10:03.400 --> 00:10:05.900
capital things, where people
will describe things that

00:10:05.900 --> 00:10:07.900
are going to happen some day.

00:10:07.900 --> 00:10:11.920
And a lot of that does come
true, especially around here.

00:10:11.920 --> 00:10:14.630
This is a vibrant
community, and this place

00:10:14.630 --> 00:10:16.830
stands as a testament
to sometimes there's

00:10:16.830 --> 00:10:19.110
people who have an idea about
something that has never

00:10:19.110 --> 00:10:21.490
been done before, and
we're going to do it,

00:10:21.490 --> 00:10:23.070
and it'll be spectacular.

00:10:23.070 --> 00:10:24.450
And that does happen sometimes.

00:10:24.450 --> 00:10:29.912
And it's marvelous when it does,
but I don't have to do that.

00:10:29.912 --> 00:10:31.120
I'm not a venture capitalist.

00:10:31.120 --> 00:10:33.530
It's a legitimate
discipline, but that's not

00:10:33.530 --> 00:10:34.500
what I'm good at.

00:10:37.070 --> 00:10:41.320
In Virginia, we joke about
once you do something twice,

00:10:41.320 --> 00:10:43.900
it becomes a tradition, so
they have to keep doing it

00:10:43.900 --> 00:10:45.896
unless there's some
reason not to do it.

00:10:45.896 --> 00:10:47.520
So Virginia might
have a different sort

00:10:47.520 --> 00:10:50.702
of sense about history than
what might be the case here,

00:10:50.702 --> 00:10:52.660
and thinking about things
that were in the past

00:10:52.660 --> 00:10:53.880
as opposed to the future.

00:10:53.880 --> 00:11:00.050
So I like to see a demonstrated
record of profitability.

00:11:00.050 --> 00:11:02.810
Now the other reason that I
like to see that, in addition

00:11:02.810 --> 00:11:06.220
to just my own limits, and
not having the skills to see

00:11:06.220 --> 00:11:09.000
into the future as well as
some others do, is that,

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:13.020
if you think about what a
business is designed to do,

00:11:13.020 --> 00:11:15.920
and it is to serve others.

00:11:15.920 --> 00:11:18.930
So the most successful
business you will ever find,

00:11:18.930 --> 00:11:22.490
is one that the customers are
glad they're doing business

00:11:22.490 --> 00:11:23.037
with you.

00:11:23.037 --> 00:11:25.120
Because that means their
lives are getting better.

00:11:25.120 --> 00:11:28.850
There is some value that is
being created for the customer,

00:11:28.850 --> 00:11:31.430
not for the business, but for
the customer, because of that

00:11:31.430 --> 00:11:32.890
company being in business.

00:11:32.890 --> 00:11:37.430
And the mark of the business
doing that well, is a profit.

00:11:37.430 --> 00:11:39.940
Because if you have a business
that is not making a profit,

00:11:39.940 --> 00:11:42.500
that means one of two
things is the case.

00:11:42.500 --> 00:11:45.870
A, the business is either doing
something that the world just

00:11:45.870 --> 00:11:47.100
doesn't really care about.

00:11:47.100 --> 00:11:47.810
People don't need it.

00:11:47.810 --> 00:11:48.684
People don't want it.

00:11:48.684 --> 00:11:53.150
For whatever reason, it's
not getting the recognition

00:11:53.150 --> 00:11:54.931
or demand in the
marketplace, such

00:11:54.931 --> 00:11:57.180
that the business is able
to do all the things that it

00:11:57.180 --> 00:12:00.210
needs to do, and still have
a margin of profit left over.

00:12:00.210 --> 00:12:03.480
So that's of no interest
to me, because in order

00:12:03.480 --> 00:12:05.780
to invest and
invest successfully,

00:12:05.780 --> 00:12:09.210
a business needs to be able to
have profits to pay dividends,

00:12:09.210 --> 00:12:13.440
to pay its employees, to grow
and invest over time, so I

00:12:13.440 --> 00:12:14.990
want to see a profit there.

00:12:14.990 --> 00:12:17.260
The second reason that
a business might not

00:12:17.260 --> 00:12:20.710
be profitable, is that
they're not very good at it.

00:12:20.710 --> 00:12:22.840
So I don't know
how much anybody's

00:12:22.840 --> 00:12:25.100
interested in
sports around here,

00:12:25.100 --> 00:12:27.365
but I'm the Washington
Redskins fan.

00:12:27.365 --> 00:12:29.240
And I hate to admit
that, because they're not

00:12:29.240 --> 00:12:30.400
very successful.

00:12:30.400 --> 00:12:32.880
But neither are the
Oakland Raiders,

00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:34.440
which are very close here.

00:12:34.440 --> 00:12:38.690
So those two teams are in
a decade-long competition

00:12:38.690 --> 00:12:41.300
for what the worst team
in the NFL is going to be.

00:12:41.300 --> 00:12:43.689
And I can't believe
that they do,

00:12:43.689 --> 00:12:45.730
which is kind of surprising,
but think about that

00:12:45.730 --> 00:12:48.720
as a business, that if you had
a business that's consistently

00:12:48.720 --> 00:12:50.624
at or near the
bottom of the things,

00:12:50.624 --> 00:12:52.790
you would not think that
that is very good business,

00:12:52.790 --> 00:12:55.415
and as a consequence, how could
that be a very good investment?

00:12:55.415 --> 00:12:58.351
If I really want to give some
of my hard-earned capital

00:12:58.351 --> 00:12:59.850
to that business,
and think that I'm

00:12:59.850 --> 00:13:03.410
going to get more
of it years later,

00:13:03.410 --> 00:13:05.570
I want that business
to be successful.

00:13:05.570 --> 00:13:08.075
So that's why look for
businesses that are profitable

00:13:08.075 --> 00:13:09.970
and earning good
returns on capital.

00:13:09.970 --> 00:13:13.010
And I add the part about
leverage, because again,

00:13:13.010 --> 00:13:17.722
from mistakes in the
2008-2009 financial crisis,

00:13:17.722 --> 00:13:19.896
I had some tough losses.

00:13:19.896 --> 00:13:21.270
And again, I think
you learn more

00:13:21.270 --> 00:13:25.490
from things that don't go well
then when things do go well.

00:13:25.490 --> 00:13:28.460
And I looked at some businesses
that I did not really

00:13:28.460 --> 00:13:31.420
appreciate how much leverage
was inherent in what

00:13:31.420 --> 00:13:32.214
they were doing.

00:13:32.214 --> 00:13:33.630
So if you have
financial leverage,

00:13:33.630 --> 00:13:35.090
you might have
very good business.

00:13:35.090 --> 00:13:36.690
You might be taking
care of your customers.

00:13:36.690 --> 00:13:37.981
You might be serving them well.

00:13:37.981 --> 00:13:40.060
They might be happy to
do business with you,

00:13:40.060 --> 00:13:43.140
but you might have to
refinance your debt

00:13:43.140 --> 00:13:46.220
and have capital
resupplied to you at a time

00:13:46.220 --> 00:13:48.390
when the markets just don't
want to give it to you.

00:13:48.390 --> 00:13:50.620
And if you're in that
situation, basically, that's

00:13:50.620 --> 00:13:51.760
like being a card
player and you've

00:13:51.760 --> 00:13:53.490
got some really good
cards in your hand,

00:13:53.490 --> 00:13:55.990
but somebody just comes and
rips the cards out of your hand,

00:13:55.990 --> 00:13:58.340
before you can finish
playing the hand.

00:13:58.340 --> 00:14:00.370
And I've seen that
happen firsthand.

00:14:00.370 --> 00:14:04.920
I've had gobs of flash
taken from, figuratively,

00:14:04.920 --> 00:14:05.530
not literally.

00:14:05.530 --> 00:14:08.391
I've still got my gobs
of flesh, but I've

00:14:08.391 --> 00:14:09.890
seen that, so as a
consequence, I've

00:14:09.890 --> 00:14:11.490
become very sensitive
about leverage

00:14:11.490 --> 00:14:14.230
and not having
too much leverage.

00:14:14.230 --> 00:14:16.310
There's also another
factor of leverage,

00:14:16.310 --> 00:14:17.700
and that is character.

00:14:17.700 --> 00:14:20.980
And I'll segue into the
my second lens in a bit.

00:14:20.980 --> 00:14:23.460
And I remember when
Markel first started down

00:14:23.460 --> 00:14:26.880
the path of buying
non-insurance businesses

00:14:26.880 --> 00:14:30.880
and expanding what we did, there
was one elderly gentleman who

00:14:30.880 --> 00:14:34.100
gave me a spectacularly
good piece of advice.

00:14:34.100 --> 00:14:36.530
And he said, if you're
looking to buy businesses,

00:14:36.530 --> 00:14:39.710
don't buy businesses where
they use a lot of debt.

00:14:39.710 --> 00:14:41.140
And I wondered why.

00:14:41.140 --> 00:14:42.730
And he said, well,
if you want to make

00:14:42.730 --> 00:14:44.938
sure you're dealing with
high-quality, high-integrity

00:14:44.938 --> 00:14:47.860
people, generally speaking,
high-quality, high-integrity

00:14:47.860 --> 00:14:49.220
people don't use a lot of debt.

00:14:49.220 --> 00:14:52.400
Or not so much that, but
if you're a bad person,

00:14:52.400 --> 00:14:54.540
if you were sort of a
little bit of a crook

00:14:54.540 --> 00:14:56.710
or had a little bit of
larceny in your heart,

00:14:56.710 --> 00:15:01.204
it's unlikely that you would
use 100% equity finance.

00:15:01.204 --> 00:15:02.620
Because when it's
equity financed,

00:15:02.620 --> 00:15:04.507
it means it's your own money.

00:15:04.507 --> 00:15:06.340
When it's debt, you're
running your business

00:15:06.340 --> 00:15:07.340
on other people's money.

00:15:07.340 --> 00:15:11.330
He says crooks don't
steal their own money.

00:15:11.330 --> 00:15:13.840
They steal other people's money.

00:15:13.840 --> 00:15:16.570
So when you see a business
that sort of relies

00:15:16.570 --> 00:15:20.760
on a bunch of debt to
operate and be successful,

00:15:20.760 --> 00:15:25.810
that adds a layer of concern or
diligence that you have to do,

00:15:25.810 --> 00:15:27.841
that you have to think
about that you don't have

00:15:27.841 --> 00:15:29.840
to if you look at the
business that just doesn't

00:15:29.840 --> 00:15:30.990
use very much debt.

00:15:30.990 --> 00:15:32.300
So it's a margin of safety.

00:15:32.300 --> 00:15:35.480
That's a word and a phrase that
Ben Graham used quite a bit

00:15:35.480 --> 00:15:39.940
in thinking about investing,
by looking at companies

00:15:39.940 --> 00:15:41.940
that don't use much debt.

00:15:41.940 --> 00:15:43.885
That just really
protects your downside

00:15:43.885 --> 00:15:47.200
and protects you from
bad things happening.

00:15:47.200 --> 00:15:48.930
The second lens that
I look at anything

00:15:48.930 --> 00:15:53.241
through is the management
and the management teams

00:15:53.241 --> 00:15:54.490
that are running the business.

00:15:54.490 --> 00:15:57.690
I'm not running these businesses
that either we invest in

00:15:57.690 --> 00:16:01.000
as shareholders and buy
stock in, or that we buy,

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:05.950
that we're majority owners
of or 100% owners of.

00:16:05.950 --> 00:16:09.380
I mean, there are people who
are running these businesses,

00:16:09.380 --> 00:16:12.080
and those people will
make those businesses

00:16:12.080 --> 00:16:15.836
the success or failure
that they are doomed to be.

00:16:15.836 --> 00:16:18.460
And when I'm looking at people,
I'm looking for two attributes.

00:16:18.460 --> 00:16:22.760
One is I want
character, integrity.

00:16:22.760 --> 00:16:24.360
And ability.

00:16:24.360 --> 00:16:28.890
Two things: character
and the ability.

00:16:28.890 --> 00:16:30.900
Because one without
the other is worthless.

00:16:30.900 --> 00:16:33.570
If you have people who
have high integrity,

00:16:33.570 --> 00:16:36.420
they're good character people,
but they're not very talented--

00:16:36.420 --> 00:16:37.860
well, they may be nice people.

00:16:37.860 --> 00:16:38.610
You may like them.

00:16:38.610 --> 00:16:40.770
They may be good
friends, good neighbors,

00:16:40.770 --> 00:16:43.200
good coaches of your
kid's soccer team,

00:16:43.200 --> 00:16:44.280
things of that nature.

00:16:44.280 --> 00:16:47.860
But in the context of business,
they can't get the job done.

00:16:47.860 --> 00:16:50.010
So as a consequence, that
doesn't do you any good,

00:16:50.010 --> 00:16:51.510
because the business
does have to be

00:16:51.510 --> 00:16:54.100
profitable to continue
to persist and grow

00:16:54.100 --> 00:16:57.370
and last over long
periods of time.

00:16:57.370 --> 00:17:01.560
So you got to see
that talent there.

00:17:01.560 --> 00:17:03.950
The character is nice,
but it is not sufficient

00:17:03.950 --> 00:17:05.380
in and of itself.

00:17:05.380 --> 00:17:08.710
If you have people who are
talented, who are whip-smart,

00:17:08.710 --> 00:17:11.900
who are very skilled at
what they do, but yet

00:17:11.900 --> 00:17:15.770
have a character or integrity
flaw of some sort-- well,

00:17:15.770 --> 00:17:18.460
they may do well,
but you as there

00:17:18.460 --> 00:17:22.329
outside, silent,
non-controlling partner are not.

00:17:22.329 --> 00:17:25.190
That will not end well.

00:17:25.190 --> 00:17:27.730
And again, I'll get
to your questions

00:17:27.730 --> 00:17:29.260
in just a few
minutes, I sure will.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:33.810
That's not just
about picking stocks,

00:17:33.810 --> 00:17:35.350
that's about relationships.

00:17:35.350 --> 00:17:38.750
So if you're picking a spouse,
or a partner in a venture--

00:17:38.750 --> 00:17:40.010
anything like that.

00:17:40.010 --> 00:17:42.700
To see both of those
features in place

00:17:42.700 --> 00:17:44.460
in large enough
quantities, that you

00:17:44.460 --> 00:17:46.170
have confidence
that you're dealing

00:17:46.170 --> 00:17:49.200
with people of character
and integrity and talent.

00:17:49.200 --> 00:17:52.015
That's an important
thing to look for.

00:17:52.015 --> 00:17:55.800
In fact, I can't think of
anything that's more important.

00:17:55.800 --> 00:17:58.540
I'll go through four
bits, four lenses,

00:17:58.540 --> 00:18:01.260
and then we'll start opening
the floor for questions.

00:18:01.260 --> 00:18:03.000
The third thing that
I think about when

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:06.075
investing in anything, is what
are the reinvestment dynamics

00:18:06.075 --> 00:18:07.315
of the business?

00:18:07.315 --> 00:18:09.860
And that's a somewhat
complicated way

00:18:09.860 --> 00:18:12.607
of saying things.

00:18:12.607 --> 00:18:14.440
[INAUDIBLE], as a
graduate of the University

00:18:14.440 --> 00:18:16.690
of Pennsylvania-- we were
chatting about this earlier.

00:18:16.690 --> 00:18:19.140
So Ben Franklin was
the founder of Penn,

00:18:19.140 --> 00:18:22.600
and sort of the revered
figure of the Penn Quakers.

00:18:22.600 --> 00:18:25.380
And Ben Franklin said
money makes more money,

00:18:25.380 --> 00:18:27.590
and the money money
makes, makes more money.

00:18:27.590 --> 00:18:31.740
So he intuitively understood
the power of compound interest.

00:18:31.740 --> 00:18:34.300
Einstein said it was the most
powerful force in the universe,

00:18:34.300 --> 00:18:35.290
compound interest.

00:18:35.290 --> 00:18:37.230
Einstein further went
on to say, that those

00:18:37.230 --> 00:18:40.650
who understand compound
interest earn it and those who

00:18:40.650 --> 00:18:42.680
do not understand it pay it.

00:18:42.680 --> 00:18:45.550
So what is the reinvestment
dynamic of the business?

00:18:45.550 --> 00:18:47.222
What's the compounding feature?

00:18:47.222 --> 00:18:49.180
And one of the ways you
could think about that,

00:18:49.180 --> 00:18:51.770
is think about the
restaurant business.

00:18:51.770 --> 00:18:57.950
In a spectacular five-star,
gourmet, lovely restaurant--

00:18:57.950 --> 00:19:01.600
typically, those tend to
be owned by the people who

00:19:01.600 --> 00:19:03.350
are there every day.

00:19:03.350 --> 00:19:08.430
They're not chains of the
best restaurants in the world,

00:19:08.430 --> 00:19:09.920
from sort of a
gourmet perspective.

00:19:09.920 --> 00:19:12.037
Usually the owner is
the chef, or right there

00:19:12.037 --> 00:19:13.120
in the front of the house.

00:19:13.120 --> 00:19:14.286
And he's there all the time.

00:19:14.286 --> 00:19:16.120
So that business,
that restaurant,

00:19:16.120 --> 00:19:17.860
can be very successful.

00:19:17.860 --> 00:19:19.770
But typically,
that is not a model

00:19:19.770 --> 00:19:22.840
that is set up to be able to
replicate it again and again

00:19:22.840 --> 00:19:24.370
and again and again and again.

00:19:24.370 --> 00:19:26.500
It may provide a
very nice living

00:19:26.500 --> 00:19:30.170
for the owner and their
family, and employ

00:19:30.170 --> 00:19:34.400
their family, and great service
to the world, great food,

00:19:34.400 --> 00:19:37.224
great prices, all that sort of
stuff, but it's not replicable.

00:19:37.224 --> 00:19:38.890
So there are some
businesses that you'll

00:19:38.890 --> 00:19:41.830
see that are like that,
that are boutiques,

00:19:41.830 --> 00:19:42.980
in some form or fashion.

00:19:42.980 --> 00:19:45.855
It's a limiting factor to
really be able to apply capital

00:19:45.855 --> 00:19:47.210
and to see it grow.

00:19:47.210 --> 00:19:49.850
There are other
businesses, and in the news

00:19:49.850 --> 00:19:52.270
these days that people may
wonder whether their time has

00:19:52.270 --> 00:19:54.860
passed, and I won't
enter into that debate,

00:19:54.860 --> 00:19:58.120
but clearly this would be
an example of where somebody

00:19:58.120 --> 00:20:00.350
was able to figure out
a restaurant model that

00:20:00.350 --> 00:20:02.850
was able to be replicable, and
able to be done over and over

00:20:02.850 --> 00:20:03.750
and over again.

00:20:03.750 --> 00:20:08.450
But go back in time 50 years,
and at the start of McDonald's.

00:20:08.450 --> 00:20:11.130
And then another McDonald's and
another McDonald's and another

00:20:11.130 --> 00:20:12.100
McDonald's.

00:20:12.100 --> 00:20:13.560
One right after the other.

00:20:13.560 --> 00:20:16.530
That's a perfect example
of where that reinvestment

00:20:16.530 --> 00:20:17.720
dynamic kicks in.

00:20:17.720 --> 00:20:21.110
So what I'm looking at
something, I'm thinking how big

00:20:21.110 --> 00:20:22.190
can this be?

00:20:22.190 --> 00:20:23.570
How scalable is it?

00:20:23.570 --> 00:20:24.820
How replicable is it?

00:20:24.820 --> 00:20:27.790
Because in order for you to
really apply a bunch of capital

00:20:27.790 --> 00:20:30.100
to it, it has to be
something that you

00:20:30.100 --> 00:20:31.940
can keep reinvesting in.

00:20:31.940 --> 00:20:34.282
And if you think about
things in a spectrum,

00:20:34.282 --> 00:20:35.990
and I would encourage
you to always think

00:20:35.990 --> 00:20:38.770
about things in more than one
dimension and in a spectrum.

00:20:38.770 --> 00:20:41.334
Things, generally
speaking, are not binary.

00:20:41.334 --> 00:20:42.250
They're not yes or no.

00:20:42.250 --> 00:20:43.590
They're not white or black.

00:20:43.590 --> 00:20:47.090
They're shades of gray all
the way along the line.

00:20:47.090 --> 00:20:49.300
So a perfect
business is one that

00:20:49.300 --> 00:20:51.800
earns very good
returns on its capital,

00:20:51.800 --> 00:20:54.980
and can take that capital that
it makes and then reinvest that

00:20:54.980 --> 00:20:58.330
and keep compounding at the
same sort of a rate year

00:20:58.330 --> 00:20:59.300
after year after year.

00:20:59.300 --> 00:21:00.370
That's the North Star.

00:21:00.370 --> 00:21:02.189
That would be the
absolute perfection.

00:21:02.189 --> 00:21:03.730
The worst kind of
business is the one

00:21:03.730 --> 00:21:06.100
that doesn't earn very
good returns on capital,

00:21:06.100 --> 00:21:09.300
and yet seems to need
gobs of it all the time.

00:21:09.300 --> 00:21:10.954
And again, this
might be old data,

00:21:10.954 --> 00:21:12.370
because the world
seems to change,

00:21:12.370 --> 00:21:15.840
but I used to joke that
airlines fit that category.

00:21:15.840 --> 00:21:17.380
So there were all
these airlines,

00:21:17.380 --> 00:21:19.610
and they realize what
was coming and going.

00:21:19.610 --> 00:21:21.860
And people seem to want to
always get in the business,

00:21:21.860 --> 00:21:24.040
but they never really make
good returns on capital.

00:21:24.040 --> 00:21:25.000
These days they are.

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:28.210
Whether they will continue to
do so or not, I don't know.

00:21:28.210 --> 00:21:30.170
But that's kind of the
spectrum of business,

00:21:30.170 --> 00:21:32.980
so I just try to get as close
to this end of the spectrum as

00:21:32.980 --> 00:21:34.190
possible.

00:21:34.190 --> 00:21:37.580
Now in the real world,
this does not really

00:21:37.580 --> 00:21:39.330
exist very often
or very frequently

00:21:39.330 --> 00:21:42.310
and oftentimes it's very
richly priced when you see it.

00:21:42.310 --> 00:21:44.380
But how close can you get to it?

00:21:44.380 --> 00:21:47.230
Because the second-best
business in the world,

00:21:47.230 --> 00:21:49.890
is one that earns a very
good returns on capital.

00:21:49.890 --> 00:21:53.170
It can't reinvest it, but
the management knows that.

00:21:53.170 --> 00:21:55.550
They're intellectually
honest that they

00:21:55.550 --> 00:21:57.660
have to do something
else with the money.

00:21:57.660 --> 00:21:58.830
And what are their choices?

00:21:58.830 --> 00:22:00.737
Well, they can
make acquisitions,

00:22:00.737 --> 00:22:03.070
they can pay dividends, they
can buy in their own stock.

00:22:03.070 --> 00:22:05.030
But they are thoughtful
and they know that.

00:22:05.030 --> 00:22:06.970
And Berkshire really
is the best example

00:22:06.970 --> 00:22:09.360
of a company that
had that in place,

00:22:09.360 --> 00:22:12.357
where you had the
genius at the top who

00:22:12.357 --> 00:22:13.940
knew that the original
business, which

00:22:13.940 --> 00:22:17.520
was a textile business--
whatever money that made,

00:22:17.520 --> 00:22:20.190
it was best to invest
that somewhere else.

00:22:20.190 --> 00:22:23.520
And that's what Buffett
has done for 50 years,

00:22:23.520 --> 00:22:27.290
is to reinvest the cash flows
of the various businesses

00:22:27.290 --> 00:22:30.930
the come feed into
Berkshire in other places,

00:22:30.930 --> 00:22:35.350
so that is the maestro-like
effect that he has had.

00:22:35.350 --> 00:22:38.400
So that's a legitimate way of
handling the notion that you

00:22:38.400 --> 00:22:41.350
can't reinvest in the
business that you have,

00:22:41.350 --> 00:22:43.220
but you can be thoughtful
about what you do

00:22:43.220 --> 00:22:44.980
that money when it comes in it.

00:22:44.980 --> 00:22:49.790
And then the fourth and final
lens its price, evaluation.

00:22:49.790 --> 00:22:51.680
And that's really
where a lot of people

00:22:51.680 --> 00:22:54.746
start in investing because
there are books you can read.

00:22:54.746 --> 00:22:56.370
There are spreadsheets
that you can do.

00:22:56.370 --> 00:22:58.280
There are well-trod
paths you can

00:22:58.280 --> 00:23:01.630
follow that talk about what's
a reasonable price earnings

00:23:01.630 --> 00:23:04.120
ratio, what's a reasonable
price to book ratio,

00:23:04.120 --> 00:23:05.910
or what's a reasonable
divident-- all

00:23:05.910 --> 00:23:09.060
these quantitative factors.

00:23:09.060 --> 00:23:12.820
And those are all good, but
as I said, they're not enough.

00:23:12.820 --> 00:23:14.610
They go in to the thinking.

00:23:14.610 --> 00:23:17.560
They go into the thought
process of whether this

00:23:17.560 --> 00:23:20.210
is a good investment
or not, but the mistake

00:23:20.210 --> 00:23:23.780
that I see-- there's
two types of mistakes

00:23:23.780 --> 00:23:26.910
you could make when you're
doing your evaluation work.

00:23:26.910 --> 00:23:30.710
One is that you pay
too much for something.

00:23:30.710 --> 00:23:33.260
So you make this judgment
about what something is worth,

00:23:33.260 --> 00:23:35.450
or you make an error
in those calculations,

00:23:35.450 --> 00:23:37.380
and you pay more than
something is worth.

00:23:37.380 --> 00:23:39.900
And that that's a
frustrating error,

00:23:39.900 --> 00:23:42.160
but you've laid out some
money and it doesn't really

00:23:42.160 --> 00:23:44.104
earn much return
or less of return

00:23:44.104 --> 00:23:45.520
or maybe even loses
money compared

00:23:45.520 --> 00:23:46.746
to what you paid out for it.

00:23:46.746 --> 00:23:48.120
That's not the
worst thing that's

00:23:48.120 --> 00:23:49.950
ever going to happen to you.

00:23:49.950 --> 00:23:53.450
That's an error that
you can recover from.

00:23:53.450 --> 00:23:56.520
The kind of errors
that are harder,

00:23:56.520 --> 00:23:58.740
and that really cost
you more, although it's

00:23:58.740 --> 00:24:01.230
a hidden cost and
it's an implicit cost,

00:24:01.230 --> 00:24:04.210
is that you've thought about
what something was worth,

00:24:04.210 --> 00:24:06.600
and you thought about what
you wanted to pay for,

00:24:06.600 --> 00:24:09.280
and this was something
that actually did compound,

00:24:09.280 --> 00:24:11.640
and you never bought
it, because it never

00:24:11.640 --> 00:24:13.780
met your test evaluation.

00:24:13.780 --> 00:24:16.260
But it's just kept on
compounding over time.

00:24:16.260 --> 00:24:20.440
That example, it's easy
not to talk about it.

00:24:20.440 --> 00:24:24.290
And I think if there's
one thing that I've

00:24:24.290 --> 00:24:28.650
been thinking about a lot
recently is as human beings,

00:24:28.650 --> 00:24:33.520
we tend to have very vivid
memories of things that we did

00:24:33.520 --> 00:24:35.270
and things that happened
to us, especially

00:24:35.270 --> 00:24:36.970
things that happened
to us recently.

00:24:36.970 --> 00:24:39.640
We tend to not
have vivid memories

00:24:39.640 --> 00:24:42.330
and not do well about
thinking about the things

00:24:42.330 --> 00:24:45.130
that didn't happen to
us or that we didn't do.

00:24:45.130 --> 00:24:49.460
And we can brush away those
experiences relatively easily,

00:24:49.460 --> 00:24:51.530
because we don't firsthand
experience with it.

00:24:51.530 --> 00:24:53.704
So we probably all have
stories about something,

00:24:53.704 --> 00:24:55.620
and the older you get,
the more stories you'll

00:24:55.620 --> 00:24:58.430
have like this, where you
thought about something

00:24:58.430 --> 00:25:00.850
or you thought something
might have been a good idea,

00:25:00.850 --> 00:25:02.190
or you thought that might
have been good business,

00:25:02.190 --> 00:25:03.690
or you thought that might
have been a good stock.

00:25:03.690 --> 00:25:05.110
In a certain point in time.

00:25:05.110 --> 00:25:08.780
But for whatever reason,
pricing or whatever,

00:25:08.780 --> 00:25:11.050
you didn't buy it at
that time, and then

00:25:11.050 --> 00:25:13.410
you never got
around to buying it.

00:25:13.410 --> 00:25:15.310
Those are the things
that really hurt.

00:25:15.310 --> 00:25:18.290
That money that you
didn't make, will

00:25:18.290 --> 00:25:21.140
end up being a far
bigger subtraction

00:25:21.140 --> 00:25:24.640
from your theoretical end
net worth, then the things

00:25:24.640 --> 00:25:26.470
that you did buy that
perhaps did not work

00:25:26.470 --> 00:25:30.000
as well as you hoped it would.

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:33.040
So those are the four
points, and the four lenses

00:25:33.040 --> 00:25:35.930
of how I think about
investing and how

00:25:35.930 --> 00:25:38.370
I've learned to
think differently

00:25:38.370 --> 00:25:41.180
than the way I thought when
I was first starting out

00:25:41.180 --> 00:25:42.600
as an accountant.

00:25:42.600 --> 00:25:44.055
I was very
quantitatively-driven.

00:25:44.055 --> 00:25:47.480
I was very disciplined about
sticking to certain metrics

00:25:47.480 --> 00:25:51.480
that I thought were
markers of valuation.

00:25:51.480 --> 00:25:54.850
And I'm started to think
more qualitatively.

00:25:54.850 --> 00:25:57.080
And if there was
one of those four

00:25:57.080 --> 00:25:59.130
that's the one that I
would think about the most,

00:25:59.130 --> 00:26:01.980
it would be the third
point, the reinvestment.

00:26:01.980 --> 00:26:04.680
What will happen over
time to this business?

00:26:04.680 --> 00:26:05.460
Will get better?

00:26:05.460 --> 00:26:06.870
Will it get worse?

00:26:06.870 --> 00:26:10.302
Are the conditions behind it
improving or deteriorating?

00:26:10.302 --> 00:26:11.510
And it's a tough world.

00:26:11.510 --> 00:26:12.230
It's tough.

00:26:12.230 --> 00:26:15.240
It is very tough to find things
that you have confidence in,

00:26:15.240 --> 00:26:20.364
that will continue in
your best judgment,

00:26:20.364 --> 00:26:22.280
to continue to compounding
in value over time.

00:26:22.280 --> 00:26:25.150
But when you do that,
don't be a penny pincher--

00:26:25.150 --> 00:26:28.340
and I'm as tight as they come--
but don't be a penny pincher

00:26:28.340 --> 00:26:31.030
when you find
businesses like that.

00:26:31.030 --> 00:26:34.380
So with that, I want to stop
and start taking some questions.

00:26:34.380 --> 00:26:36.170
And I know sir, you did.

00:26:36.170 --> 00:26:38.430
AUDIENCE: So you
mentioned evaluating

00:26:38.430 --> 00:26:41.450
management-- you think about
character and integrity.

00:26:41.450 --> 00:26:44.840
First question is, how do you
actually, specifically evaluate

00:26:44.840 --> 00:26:45.720
that?

00:26:45.720 --> 00:26:49.720
And for us that can actually
interact with management

00:26:49.720 --> 00:26:53.090
of companies, and we just look
at prices and stuff like that,

00:26:53.090 --> 00:26:56.230
how do we actually go
about figuring that out?

00:26:56.230 --> 00:27:00.340
TOM GAYNER: Well again,
I'm looking around the room

00:27:00.340 --> 00:27:03.430
and I'm seeing that I'm older
than you guys, but I'm married,

00:27:03.430 --> 00:27:05.050
and I've been
married a long time.

00:27:05.050 --> 00:27:08.190
Just by show of hands, some
of the people who are married?

00:27:08.190 --> 00:27:11.220
A bunch of you.

00:27:11.220 --> 00:27:14.740
How did you decide who
you're going to marry?

00:27:14.740 --> 00:27:15.989
You dated.

00:27:15.989 --> 00:27:17.280
And what's the point of dating?

00:27:17.280 --> 00:27:19.480
It's not really to
see a movie, or go

00:27:19.480 --> 00:27:21.880
to a restaurant, or a
ballgame or roller skating,

00:27:21.880 --> 00:27:24.450
or whatever you did.

00:27:24.450 --> 00:27:26.880
It's really to spend
time with somebody,

00:27:26.880 --> 00:27:32.050
to see if their values
overlap enough with yours,

00:27:32.050 --> 00:27:34.850
that you'll be able to get
along for a long period of time.

00:27:34.850 --> 00:27:37.220
That's the whole
point of dating.

00:27:37.220 --> 00:27:41.060
And with management teams,
and people running businesses,

00:27:41.060 --> 00:27:45.270
in effect, what I'm doing,
is analogous to the idea

00:27:45.270 --> 00:27:46.080
of dating.

00:27:46.080 --> 00:27:49.150
It's to try to find people
running these businesses where

00:27:49.150 --> 00:27:51.240
our values, at least in
the worlds of commerce,

00:27:51.240 --> 00:27:54.800
overlap enough that I'm
happy for them to have

00:27:54.800 --> 00:27:58.080
the responsibility and authority
to run that business as they

00:27:58.080 --> 00:28:00.160
see fit.

00:28:00.160 --> 00:28:03.870
Now you mentioned a
limitation, that you

00:28:03.870 --> 00:28:07.120
suggest that I'm able
to get an appointment

00:28:07.120 --> 00:28:11.230
and see people who run business
and interact with the managers

00:28:11.230 --> 00:28:12.940
and to some degree, that's true.

00:28:12.940 --> 00:28:16.970
But at the same time, I
really spend a lot more time

00:28:16.970 --> 00:28:21.170
reading about people, and
using the exact same resources

00:28:21.170 --> 00:28:23.680
that you would have
access to as well.

00:28:23.680 --> 00:28:25.440
So I read the annual reports.

00:28:25.440 --> 00:28:26.950
I read the proxy statements.

00:28:26.950 --> 00:28:28.410
I read magazine articles.

00:28:28.410 --> 00:28:31.990
And I try to think
and just sort of look,

00:28:31.990 --> 00:28:36.220
and get a gut feel
and make some judgment

00:28:36.220 --> 00:28:38.250
and discernment about
whether these people are

00:28:38.250 --> 00:28:41.760
acting in a way
that's reasonable

00:28:41.760 --> 00:28:43.910
and makes sense to me.

00:28:43.910 --> 00:28:45.862
And your calibration
is going to be

00:28:45.862 --> 00:28:47.070
somewhat different than mine.

00:28:47.070 --> 00:28:48.350
You're just different.

00:28:48.350 --> 00:28:50.030
All of us are going
to set those things

00:28:50.030 --> 00:28:52.400
that we think are
important, and where

00:28:52.400 --> 00:28:55.670
we think the bounds of behavior
should be, differently.

00:28:55.670 --> 00:28:59.030
Because we're all different,
but you have them.

00:28:59.030 --> 00:29:03.199
And I encourage you to think
about things in that dimension,

00:29:03.199 --> 00:29:04.740
because one of the
things you'll find

00:29:04.740 --> 00:29:06.420
is, you'll make a judgment.

00:29:06.420 --> 00:29:08.510
Your judgment will
not be perfect,

00:29:08.510 --> 00:29:11.270
but by virtue of the
times you get it wrong,

00:29:11.270 --> 00:29:13.210
when make an error,
you'll learn something.

00:29:13.210 --> 00:29:15.776
It's like, ooh, I don't
like that so much.

00:29:15.776 --> 00:29:17.150
And that will be
a marker to you,

00:29:17.150 --> 00:29:20.570
that the next time you see it,
you will be sensitized to it

00:29:20.570 --> 00:29:23.200
and it will help you
make better judgments.

00:29:23.200 --> 00:29:29.040
In looking at you guys, when I
first started in the investment

00:29:29.040 --> 00:29:32.260
business, I have a
very wonderful mentor

00:29:32.260 --> 00:29:33.940
named Ned Reynolds.

00:29:33.940 --> 00:29:36.220
And this was a gentleman
who's probably 70 years old

00:29:36.220 --> 00:29:38.710
and I was brand new in
the investment business.

00:29:38.710 --> 00:29:40.510
And he was very
interesting character,

00:29:40.510 --> 00:29:43.480
and it's not like he
was formally my mentor,

00:29:43.480 --> 00:29:45.250
he was nice.

00:29:45.250 --> 00:29:48.510
He was kind and he was
just helpful to people.

00:29:48.510 --> 00:29:51.160
And one day, I happened
to be standing next to him

00:29:51.160 --> 00:29:53.800
on a hot, summer day
in Richmond, Virginia.

00:29:53.800 --> 00:29:56.820
And not much was going on.

00:29:56.820 --> 00:30:00.610
We were just sort of-- market
was open, and in those days,

00:30:00.610 --> 00:30:02.530
you didn't have the CNBC
with the ticker tape

00:30:02.530 --> 00:30:04.946
but you actually had a physical
ticker tape in a brokerage

00:30:04.946 --> 00:30:07.860
office, so it would create
this sort of hum and drone

00:30:07.860 --> 00:30:10.320
of this tape going by.

00:30:10.320 --> 00:30:11.960
And he was standing there.

00:30:11.960 --> 00:30:13.530
And he had his arms
folded like this,

00:30:13.530 --> 00:30:16.220
and he really wasn't engaged
in conversation with me.

00:30:16.220 --> 00:30:19.170
He was standing by my side,
was not making eye contact,

00:30:19.170 --> 00:30:22.470
but I had been in the business
for three months at this point.

00:30:22.470 --> 00:30:33.390
And he said, Tom, the secret
to success in the investing

00:30:33.390 --> 00:30:37.270
is lasting the first 30 years.

00:30:43.710 --> 00:30:45.670
It's a powerful statement.

00:30:45.670 --> 00:30:48.980
What he said is, everything you
see in the world of finance,

00:30:48.980 --> 00:30:50.740
you will see again.

00:30:50.740 --> 00:30:54.460
And every excess
that you see happen

00:30:54.460 --> 00:30:58.140
and not just over-valuation,
but under-valuation.

00:30:58.140 --> 00:31:00.530
So like the '08, '09 period
when we had a real financial

00:31:00.530 --> 00:31:06.150
crisis-- I suspect and I hope
that that's a once-a-generation

00:31:06.150 --> 00:31:07.220
kind of event.

00:31:07.220 --> 00:31:09.620
I don't think we'll go
through that again real soon,

00:31:09.620 --> 00:31:12.600
because all of us who lived
through it in a firsthand way

00:31:12.600 --> 00:31:16.660
have had a taste of that and
we don't want to do it again.

00:31:16.660 --> 00:31:19.540
And anybody who hasn't
had that happen to them,

00:31:19.540 --> 00:31:20.632
they think it can't.

00:31:20.632 --> 00:31:22.840
But you just sort of have
to have to live through it.

00:31:22.840 --> 00:31:25.190
There's an old joke that
says, every generation

00:31:25.190 --> 00:31:29.060
is the one that thinks
that they invented sex.

00:31:29.060 --> 00:31:31.980
Not so.

00:31:31.980 --> 00:31:33.750
But everybody has
that sense about them

00:31:33.750 --> 00:31:36.041
as they go through this path,
and once you've sort have

00:31:36.041 --> 00:31:38.520
been around for a while,
you sort of see things,

00:31:38.520 --> 00:31:39.710
and you recognize things.

00:31:39.710 --> 00:31:43.360
And making those judgments
about the character

00:31:43.360 --> 00:31:45.470
and the values in the way
people behave, in a way

00:31:45.470 --> 00:31:51.040
that works for you-- that's just
a process of trial and error,

00:31:51.040 --> 00:31:53.100
with an emphasis on error.

00:31:53.100 --> 00:31:54.740
And you get to it eventually.

00:31:57.825 --> 00:32:00.200
If we're talking about selecting
stocks, or buying stock,

00:32:00.200 --> 00:32:03.140
or buying investments,
you don't need

00:32:03.140 --> 00:32:05.950
to have a personal
relationship with the CEO

00:32:05.950 --> 00:32:09.670
in order to make a reasonable
judgment about whether you

00:32:09.670 --> 00:32:11.620
think that company's
being run well or not.

00:32:11.620 --> 00:32:16.500
There's a good paper trail
and a good set of evidence

00:32:16.500 --> 00:32:21.732
out there for you to think
about and draw judgments about.

00:32:21.732 --> 00:32:23.190
AUDIENCE: My question
is how do you

00:32:23.190 --> 00:32:24.770
feel about investing
in companies

00:32:24.770 --> 00:32:26.910
in rapidly-changing industries?

00:32:26.910 --> 00:32:29.860
So versus like a brand name
company like Coca Cola?

00:32:29.860 --> 00:32:32.600
TOM GAYNER: It's harder.

00:32:32.600 --> 00:32:34.910
It's not right or wrong,
or better or worse.

00:32:34.910 --> 00:32:36.280
It's just harder.

00:32:36.280 --> 00:32:39.870
So for instance, one of the
things that's under appreciated

00:32:39.870 --> 00:32:42.190
is that-- and
[INAUDIBLE] and I were

00:32:42.190 --> 00:32:45.330
talking about this yesterday--
so on his desk in his study,

00:32:45.330 --> 00:32:48.600
he had a book of the Graham and
Dodd security analysis, which

00:32:48.600 --> 00:32:52.240
is the equivalent of the
Bible for security analysis.

00:32:52.240 --> 00:32:54.210
Everybody has to
study Graham and Dodd,

00:32:54.210 --> 00:32:55.970
if you're going to
be in this business.

00:32:55.970 --> 00:32:59.450
And I noticed on the cover,
it said, sixth edition.

00:32:59.450 --> 00:33:03.300
And I said, well, I don't know
what the sixth edition is like.

00:33:03.300 --> 00:33:05.150
When I was in school
and I was studying it,

00:33:05.150 --> 00:33:06.800
it was the fourth edition.

00:33:06.800 --> 00:33:09.310
And I can remember on the
50th anniversary of the class

00:33:09.310 --> 00:33:13.510
or something, they came out with
a reprint of the first edition.

00:33:13.510 --> 00:33:17.112
And just for grins, I bought
it, and I said to [INAUDIBLE],

00:33:17.112 --> 00:33:19.570
I said, you might want to get
a hold of that first edition.

00:33:19.570 --> 00:33:22.300
Because the difference
between the first and fourth--

00:33:22.300 --> 00:33:24.580
it's an entirely different book.

00:33:24.580 --> 00:33:27.080
So in the first
edition, which is really

00:33:27.080 --> 00:33:29.820
the one that I would recommend
that you read-- and it might

00:33:29.820 --> 00:33:33.310
sound antique when they're
talking about railroads and all

00:33:33.310 --> 00:33:36.970
those kinds of all business,
but the concepts-- Ben Graham

00:33:36.970 --> 00:33:40.270
was a classicist as much
as he was a finance guy.

00:33:40.270 --> 00:33:44.620
He was talking about Greek
and Roman civilizations.

00:33:44.620 --> 00:33:47.170
Greek myths, and all that sort
of stuff, which are really

00:33:47.170 --> 00:33:49.930
about human nature, and values.

00:33:52.911 --> 00:33:54.660
Sorry for the long
answer to make a point,

00:33:54.660 --> 00:33:57.480
but people jump on Ben
Graham, and they think about

00:33:57.480 --> 00:33:59.960
all his qualitative
statements that he made.

00:33:59.960 --> 00:34:02.920
And when somebody says a
Graham and Dodd style investor,

00:34:02.920 --> 00:34:06.160
typically that has
come to mean, someone

00:34:06.160 --> 00:34:10.070
who's tearing apart a balance
sheet, and is a value spotter,

00:34:10.070 --> 00:34:12.540
and finding the
difference in price.

00:34:12.540 --> 00:34:14.750
But Ben Graham, in
the first edition,

00:34:14.750 --> 00:34:17.020
said that growth,
which is your point

00:34:17.020 --> 00:34:19.880
about rapid technological
change, and things are changing

00:34:19.880 --> 00:34:23.004
and you're implying
changing for the better.

00:34:23.004 --> 00:34:25.170
But you have to admit that
also sometimes things can

00:34:25.170 --> 00:34:27.920
and do change for the worse.

00:34:27.920 --> 00:34:31.570
Growth is extremely important.

00:34:31.570 --> 00:34:34.949
It's just hard to calculate
and it's hard to value that.

00:34:34.949 --> 00:34:37.805
Ben Graham further
went on in the book

00:34:37.805 --> 00:34:39.429
that he wrote that's
just a little more

00:34:39.429 --> 00:34:43.830
approachable and not so
much technically detailed

00:34:43.830 --> 00:34:46.330
as security analysis, but
the "Intelligent Investor",

00:34:46.330 --> 00:34:49.409
which he meant to write just for
anybody who wanted to pick up--

00:34:49.409 --> 00:34:51.350
should be able to
read that book.

00:34:51.350 --> 00:34:55.560
In one of the later editions
of the "Intelligent Investor",

00:34:55.560 --> 00:35:00.330
Ben Graham made the point that
he made more money in Geico,

00:35:00.330 --> 00:35:04.230
in the stock of Geico, than
in every other investment

00:35:04.230 --> 00:35:06.940
he made combined.

00:35:06.940 --> 00:35:08.540
Because Geico was
the growth company.

00:35:08.540 --> 00:35:10.290
That's the one that
got that third point

00:35:10.290 --> 00:35:12.580
about the reinvestment
dynamic right.

00:35:12.580 --> 00:35:16.620
And if you further went on
and researched that decision

00:35:16.620 --> 00:35:18.830
about how you he got to
be connected with Geico

00:35:18.830 --> 00:35:22.960
and how he got a hold of that
big block of Geico stock,

00:35:22.960 --> 00:35:25.600
he relied on his
partner Jerry Newman

00:35:25.600 --> 00:35:28.380
to make the final deal with
the family, the Goodwin family,

00:35:28.380 --> 00:35:30.930
to buy that stock.

00:35:30.930 --> 00:35:33.960
He did not get that over
the finish line himself,

00:35:33.960 --> 00:35:36.170
and he struggled
with that, because it

00:35:36.170 --> 00:35:41.610
wasn't the classic sort of
investment that he was used to.

00:35:41.610 --> 00:35:44.180
He said, if it wasn't for
Geico, you never know my name.

00:35:44.180 --> 00:35:48.580
So that idea of growth, of
rapid technological change,

00:35:48.580 --> 00:35:53.040
of changing the world-- I
mean, this is a classic example

00:35:53.040 --> 00:35:56.565
of something they did not
exist not that long ago,

00:35:56.565 --> 00:35:58.690
and now it's one of the
leading, dominant companies

00:35:58.690 --> 00:36:00.340
in the world.

00:36:00.340 --> 00:36:04.120
All you need to do is get that
right once in your whole life,

00:36:04.120 --> 00:36:07.130
and it will change your
investing career forever.

00:36:07.130 --> 00:36:08.870
But it's hard.

00:36:08.870 --> 00:36:10.340
It's hard to do that.

