00:40:56.497 --> 00:40:58.330
with a couple of
acquisitions along the way.

00:40:58.330 --> 00:40:59.640
So it's been a good ride.

00:40:59.640 --> 00:41:01.089
That's how I got there.

00:41:01.089 --> 00:41:01.880
And you're correct.

00:41:01.880 --> 00:41:04.810
One of the beautiful things
about being at Markel

00:41:04.810 --> 00:41:07.090
is it has been a
profitable insurance

00:41:07.090 --> 00:41:08.450
company all the way along.

00:41:08.450 --> 00:41:09.560
I mean, there have
been some years

00:41:09.560 --> 00:41:11.893
where they didn't make profits,
which is normal in years

00:41:11.893 --> 00:41:13.032
of heavy duty catastrophes.

00:41:13.032 --> 00:41:14.740
We're going to lose
a little bit of money

00:41:14.740 --> 00:41:17.070
on the insurance
side but not much.

00:41:17.070 --> 00:41:19.130
But more often than not,
the insurance company

00:41:19.130 --> 00:41:23.300
has been profitable and has been
putting money into the account.

00:41:23.300 --> 00:41:26.010
And then we could apply
those four lenses, those four

00:41:26.010 --> 00:41:30.060
disciplines that I spoke of
in selecting equity securities

00:41:30.060 --> 00:41:32.990
and been compounding
value that way.

00:41:32.990 --> 00:41:35.930
So for instance the day I
showed up, and the stock was $8,

00:41:35.930 --> 00:41:38.090
and now it's $800.

00:41:38.090 --> 00:41:43.150
If you do the math, in broad
brush rough terms, roughly half

00:41:43.150 --> 00:41:46.290
of that has come from cumulative
probability of insurance

00:41:46.290 --> 00:41:49.460
operations and half of it has
come from investing that money.

00:41:49.460 --> 00:41:53.360
So it's a mutually
supportive sort of deal.

00:41:53.360 --> 00:41:55.950
Now connecting that
to you individually,

00:41:55.950 --> 00:41:58.950
the great advantage that
you have individually,

00:41:58.950 --> 00:42:01.160
is that you're
investing your money.

00:42:01.160 --> 00:42:02.760
It's your money.

00:42:02.760 --> 00:42:05.800
And you don't have
a board of directors

00:42:05.800 --> 00:42:08.199
looking at you or other people.

00:42:08.199 --> 00:42:10.490
I mean, other people might
criticize what you're doing,

00:42:10.490 --> 00:42:11.970
or second-guess
what you're doing,

00:42:11.970 --> 00:42:13.720
but they have no
authority over it.

00:42:13.720 --> 00:42:14.540
It's your money.

00:42:14.540 --> 00:42:16.320
It's your decision that you get.

00:42:16.320 --> 00:42:18.180
And if you live
within your means,

00:42:18.180 --> 00:42:20.790
you have an income of this
and you're spending this,

00:42:20.790 --> 00:42:22.400
you have excess cash flow.

00:42:22.400 --> 00:42:25.720
And that excess cash flow,
you get to invest personally.

00:42:25.720 --> 00:42:27.800
And you go to invest
it for your own time

00:42:27.800 --> 00:42:31.010
horizon, your own purposes,
for as long as you want.

00:42:31.010 --> 00:42:34.590
And that's the
exact same structure

00:42:34.590 --> 00:42:35.610
that I get to live in.

00:42:35.610 --> 00:42:39.550
So I don't have
to solicit clients

00:42:39.550 --> 00:42:43.240
that may take their money
away at inopportune times.

00:42:43.240 --> 00:42:44.740
And if you look at
the studies which

00:42:44.740 --> 00:42:49.060
talk about the average
return of mutual funds

00:42:49.060 --> 00:42:51.930
over a long period
of time, is x.

00:42:51.930 --> 00:42:55.000
The average return of
investors in mutual fund

00:42:55.000 --> 00:42:56.540
is a fraction of that.

00:42:56.540 --> 00:42:57.570
Well, why?

00:42:57.570 --> 00:43:00.040
It's because when you have
a market that's like this,

00:43:00.040 --> 00:43:02.490
and it's going up,
people put money in.

00:43:02.490 --> 00:43:05.320
And when it's down like
this, they take money out.

00:43:05.320 --> 00:43:11.470
So whatever the base rates of
return are, by their behavior,

00:43:11.470 --> 00:43:12.980
they make them worse.

00:43:12.980 --> 00:43:15.570
And fortunately, in
our company, we're

00:43:15.570 --> 00:43:18.930
structured such that we try to
take that notion of the table.

00:43:18.930 --> 00:43:21.017
We're pretty much
always investing.

00:43:21.017 --> 00:43:23.100
Whether the market's doing
this, or this, or this,

00:43:23.100 --> 00:43:26.080
we're just steady pounding
away at it, and compounding.

00:43:26.080 --> 00:43:28.520
And you can do the same
thing as an individual,

00:43:28.520 --> 00:43:30.700
if you're living on
less than what you make.

00:43:30.700 --> 00:43:34.800
And I think about one of the
great, wise people of all time,

00:43:34.800 --> 00:43:35.900
is Charlie Munger.

00:43:35.900 --> 00:43:38.080
And if you think
about his example--

00:43:38.080 --> 00:43:40.550
we all know who
Charlie Munger is now.

00:43:40.550 --> 00:43:45.740
He's 92 years old-- and think
about sort of his whole life.

00:43:45.740 --> 00:43:50.980
And he started out as smart
as anybody you'll ever know.

00:43:50.980 --> 00:43:51.990
He was an attorney.

00:43:51.990 --> 00:43:54.080
I think he had seven
children if memory serves.

00:43:54.080 --> 00:43:55.413
They all went to private school.

00:43:55.413 --> 00:43:57.850
That's a lot of overhead.

00:43:57.850 --> 00:44:01.700
So I suspect, given a very
pleasant, personal lifestyle,

00:44:01.700 --> 00:44:03.780
Carlie Munger was not
a billionaire when he

00:44:03.780 --> 00:44:07.490
was 30 years old, or 25 or 35.

00:44:07.490 --> 00:44:12.510
But cumulatively, Charlie
Munger always, somehow

00:44:12.510 --> 00:44:14.450
or another, lived
on less than what

00:44:14.450 --> 00:44:16.120
he earned, so he
was creating cash

00:44:16.120 --> 00:44:19.010
flow that he was able to invest.

00:44:19.010 --> 00:44:24.180
And intrinsically, and
talking about John Wooden

00:44:24.180 --> 00:44:28.070
and having an internal
versus an external scorecard,

00:44:28.070 --> 00:44:31.470
Charlie Munger didn't care what
other people thought of him.

00:44:31.470 --> 00:44:32.189
Still doesn't.

00:44:32.189 --> 00:44:33.230
Didn't then, doesn't now.

00:44:36.250 --> 00:44:39.420
So as a consequence, just think
about this from a definition

00:44:39.420 --> 00:44:40.690
point of view.

00:44:40.690 --> 00:44:44.320
If you are living on less
than what you are making,

00:44:44.320 --> 00:44:47.300
you are Rich.

00:44:47.300 --> 00:44:47.870
Period.

00:44:47.870 --> 00:44:49.100
Paragraph.

00:44:49.100 --> 00:44:50.730
I'm not saying that
in a relative term

00:44:50.730 --> 00:44:53.840
to what other people might
be making or not making.

00:44:53.840 --> 00:44:56.636
Compared to your needs, compared
to what you're able to do,

00:44:56.636 --> 00:44:58.510
you are rich, because
there's a margin there.

00:44:58.510 --> 00:45:03.650
You have more than what you
need, by virtue of choices

00:45:03.650 --> 00:45:05.930
that you have made.

00:45:05.930 --> 00:45:08.685
Well, if you keep
doing that, and you're

00:45:08.685 --> 00:45:10.790
as smart as Charlie
Munger or at least

00:45:10.790 --> 00:45:14.221
you're smart enough to know
that he is a wise person

00:45:14.221 --> 00:45:16.470
and you should try to be as
much like him as possible.

00:45:16.470 --> 00:45:20.310
Well that gap, every year,
of positive cash flow,

00:45:20.310 --> 00:45:23.840
investing, making a
positive return, over time,

00:45:23.840 --> 00:45:25.450
begins to compound.

00:45:25.450 --> 00:45:28.760
And if you graph it on
a piece of-- not a log

00:45:28.760 --> 00:45:31.220
graph, but a regular
graph-- it'll

00:45:31.220 --> 00:45:33.560
hockey stick somewhere
along the way.

00:45:33.560 --> 00:45:37.030
So live on less than what you
make , invest it reasonably,

00:45:37.030 --> 00:45:38.170
and live a long time.

00:45:41.650 --> 00:45:44.310
It's a formula that
can't not work.

00:45:44.310 --> 00:45:45.599
And your kind enough.

