I'll just tell you one
more personal story.

00:45:47.390 --> 00:45:50.102
So I remember as a
kid, one of the things

00:45:50.102 --> 00:45:51.810
that kind of got me
hooked on this notion

00:45:51.810 --> 00:45:53.700
of compound interest
and compound returns.

00:45:53.700 --> 00:45:56.530
And I can remember this
vividly, even today.

00:45:56.530 --> 00:45:58.630
So there was this commercial.

00:45:58.630 --> 00:46:01.966
And it was about
savings and loans.

00:46:01.966 --> 00:46:04.340
which hardly even exist anymore.

00:46:04.340 --> 00:46:07.220
And it was this
picture where you only

00:46:07.220 --> 00:46:10.200
got to see this
shot from here down.

00:46:10.200 --> 00:46:12.410
So you would only see this hand.

00:46:12.410 --> 00:46:15.640
And so there was this
hand and it had $50 bills.

00:46:15.640 --> 00:46:19.620
And it was pointing out,
if you put $50 a month

00:46:19.620 --> 00:46:23.095
into your savings account
and it showed this pile being

00:46:23.095 --> 00:46:25.220
created with people putting
these $50 bills on it--

00:46:25.220 --> 00:46:26.570
it was growing.

00:46:26.570 --> 00:46:29.680
After seven years
or whatever, you'll

00:46:29.680 --> 00:46:34.780
be able to take out
$50 a month forever.

00:46:34.780 --> 00:46:36.840
And the pile you were
taking it away from

00:46:36.840 --> 00:46:39.489
was bigger than the pile
that you started with.

00:46:39.489 --> 00:46:41.280
I might have been seven
or eight years old,

00:46:41.280 --> 00:46:45.510
but a light bulb went off
for me about just the notion

00:46:45.510 --> 00:46:48.990
of compound interest
and what compound meant

00:46:48.990 --> 00:46:52.450
in a gut, visceral sense.

00:46:52.450 --> 00:46:55.848
I want to figure
something out about that.

00:46:55.848 --> 00:46:58.280
That seems pretty cool.

00:46:58.280 --> 00:47:00.905
As an individual,
structurally, as long

00:47:00.905 --> 00:47:02.280
as you can live
on less than what

00:47:02.280 --> 00:47:05.660
you make, you have
every advantage of what

00:47:05.660 --> 00:47:07.910
Berkshire has, what Markel has.

00:47:07.910 --> 00:47:12.380
There is no better structure
where the odds of success

00:47:12.380 --> 00:47:13.220
are higher.

00:47:13.220 --> 00:47:15.700
Now again, this
company stands as

00:47:15.700 --> 00:47:18.890
testament-- There are certain
times when something happens

00:47:18.890 --> 00:47:21.180
that just is out of the blue.

00:47:21.180 --> 00:47:24.300
And I call that catching
lightning in a jar.

00:47:24.300 --> 00:47:25.740
And that's what Google did.

00:47:25.740 --> 00:47:28.700
And that's what gets done
around this part of the world

00:47:28.700 --> 00:47:30.110
on a regular basis.

00:47:30.110 --> 00:47:34.720
But catching lightning in a
jar, that's really hard to do

00:47:34.720 --> 00:47:37.860
and that's really hard
to repeat, and to make

00:47:37.860 --> 00:47:42.181
that process consistent
year after year after year

00:47:42.181 --> 00:47:44.430
after year, which is much
of the challenge, I suspect,

00:47:44.430 --> 00:47:45.471
when you go back to work.

